==Biography== Born into a wealthy, [[history of the Jews in Egypt|Jewish]], family in [[Cairo]], his father was a realtor and tile factory owner, he was, nonetheless, educated in a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] school, and, upon turning 18, travelled to [[Paris]] and [[Switzerland]], in order to study art at the [[École nationale supérieure des Beaux-Arts]], eventually, in 1960, immigrating to [[Israel]], where, after serving in the [[Artillery Corps (Israel)|Artillery Corps]], taking part in the [[Six-Day War]], during the 1960s and 1970s, he gathered, around himself, a group of artists and intellectuals, calling itself "The Third Eye," a [[commune]], dedicated to [[lysergic acid diethylamide]] and [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], the ideas of [[Timothy Leary]], and, bands such as [[Pink Floyd]], [[The Moody Blues]], and, [[Grateful Dead]], which, included, amongst others, filmmakers and artists such as {{ill|Yael Aviv|he|יעל אביב}}, {{ill|Helit Yeshurun |he|הלית ישורון}}, [[Amnon Salomon]], {{ill|Daphna Arod|he|דפנה ערוד}}, {{ill|Ika Yisraeli|he|איקא ישראלי}}, and, {{ill|David Greenberg (director)|lt=David Greenberg|he|דוד גרינברג}}. He considered himself to be strongly influenced by [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] and the [[Marquis de Sade]], as well as, by [[surrealism]]'s artists such as [[André Masson]] and [[Hans Bellmer]], [[Dada]], the [[Situationist International]]'s artists such as [[Guy Debord]], the [[Beat Generation]], [[Bernard Malamud]], the band [[Faust (band)|Faust]], and, [[lettrism]], and, eventually, changed his last name, on [[Avoth Yeshurun]]'s suggestion, into a phonetic rendering of ''quatre mortes'', [[French language|French]] for "four deaths." His apartment, located at [[Dizengoff Street]] 40 in [[Tel Aviv]], where, eventually, his only film was shot, was a cornerstone of city life, during that time. He married translator, model, and, editor {{ill|Helit Yeshurun|he|הלית ישורון}}, daughter of poet [[Avoth Yeshurun]], while, working on his highly avant-garde [[1969 in film|1969]] film ''[[A Woman's Case]]'', in which, she starred, a time, during which, he met, and, casted into his film, model and [[it girl]] Ann Tochmeyer, most famous, during that period, for, appearing on the covers of magazines such as ''[[HaOlam HaZeh]]'', which, he married, after divorcing his wife, after he finished the shooting.<ref>{{cite news|last=Slavick|first=Jean|script-title=he:הערב עם ז׳אק מורי־קתמור|trans-title=Tonight, with Jacques Mory-Katmor|date=30 October 1969|url=http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_Heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=%2FZBcyTM2efPLRDKhPPbd2rV2nYdsaSQH9%2Fa3GO3vj8KEQHwqXyqQ86Nuk9%2FfrauOYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=MAR%2f1969%2f10%2f30&page=20&rtl=true|language=Hebrew|work=[[Davar]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=3 April 2017}}</ref> The film was a commercial failure, and, hindered his ability to pursue his career as a filmmaker. Other works included creating television programs showcasing the works of artists such as [[Moshe Gershuni]], [[Yosl Bergner]] (1971), [[Yaacov Agam]] (1973), and, [[Michail Grobman]] (1974).<ref>{{cite news|script-title=he:'''מקרה אישה''' + '''מסע'''|trans-title=''[[A Woman's Case]]'' + ''Masa''|url=http://www.cinema.co.il/movies/movie.aspx?movieId=7730|language=Hebrew|work=[[Tel Aviv Cinematheque]]|access-date=4 April 2017}}</ref> Some years later, around 1974, he left [[Israel]] for [[Cambodia]], [[Canada]], and, [[Thailand]], with Tochmeyer leaving for [[San Francisco]], and, finally, later, around 1975, for [[Amsterdam]], together with Tochmeyer, returning in 1991. Reportedly, while abroad, they both became addicted to [[cocaine]] and [[heroin]], while, [[squatting]] in abject poverty, forcing him to work in [[pornography]], and, Tochmeyer, to work as a stripper, while, essentially, living in a sort of [[open relationship]], together with artist {{ill|Buki Greenberg|he|בוקי גרינברג}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Anderman|first=Nirit|date=30 December 2011|script-title=he:מקרה איש: עשר שנים למותו של ז'אק קתמור|trans-title=A Man's Case: A Decade Since Jacques Katmor's Death|url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/1.1604723|language=Hebrew|work=[[Haaretz]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Barry|date=13 January 2012|title=Keeping an Eye Open|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Music/Keeping-an-eye-open|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|location=Jerusalem|access-date=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sangbleumagazine.com/2014/03/24/jacques-katmor/|title=Jacques Katmor|last=Sharpe|first=Zoe|website=[[Sang Bleu]]|date=24 March 2014|access-date=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/sight-sound-magazine/features/reopening-third-eye|title=Reopening the Third Eye|last=Sélavy|first=Virginie|last2=Shani|first2=Tal|date=24 November 2016|website=''[[British Film Institute]]''|access-date=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Grossman|first=Hagit|date=22 March 2012|script-title=he:הוזה אל האינסוף|trans-title=Hallucinating Infinitely|url=https://musaf-shabbat.com/2012/03/22/%D7%94%D7%95%D7%96%D7%94-%D7%90%D7%9C-%D7%94%D7%90%D7%99%D7%A0%D7%A1%D7%95%D7%A3-%D7%97%D7%92%D7%99%D7%AA-%D7%92%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%A1%D7%9E%D7%9F/|language=Hebrew|work=[[Makor Rishon]]|location=Jerusalem|access-date=3 April 2017}}</ref> Officially, the cause of his death was listed as [[alcoholism]]-related.<ref>{{cite news|last=Frosh|first=Tahel|date=17 August 2009|script-title=he:ז׳אק קתמור, מקרה גבר|trans-title=Jacques Katmor, a Man's Case|url=http://www.mouse.co.il/gallery/1.3338888|language=Hebrew|work=[[Ha'ir]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=3 April 2017}}</ref>
